12. This being assumed, conscience, like knowledge, has four senses:

First and most properly, it is used for the conclusion at the end of the two syllogisms, this being the ultimate judgment of the practical intellect3 as when a man says, My conscience forbids me to commit this theft. This, our author says, is the Syneidesis, as distinguished ..from the Synteresis. But see Elem. of Morality, Art. 263.

Secondly3 Conscience is used for the knowledge of the first prin- ciples of the above reasoning 3 which principles we know by the light of nature3 as when we say, My conscience tells me that nothing unjust is to be done.
